76561197999409210,Not Recommended,218410,32610312,Posted: 20 June,all,-=SOI=- Faren,"This is one of the only games where I wish there was a 'meh', rather than a distinct yes or no. On the one hand as a veteran of this genre I always feel games that lack the combinatory variation of gemcraft are horribly limited, yet the charm of the game and humble devotion of the dev team are the strength in this title and I expect the next release to live up to every expectation and more.But sadly this one for that reason alone didn't quite do it for me.It's a decent TD don't get me wrong, but the lack of strategic complexity coupled with old school linear progression let it down tremendously.Edit: It deeply saddens me that the community have come here with the specific intention of downvoting my review that I consider to be honest and not at all biased and therefore was written with the sole intention of offering an alternative perspective to those who don't own a game that they are considering purchasing.Too many times I have purchased games based off upvoted comments alone, where the community who already own that game have been very active in downvoting any comment that doesn't fit their narrative.Steam need to look at the voting system. If you didn't find this review helpful then I suspect you already own the game. Therefore the review system means very little to you. Unless you're a dev.--------------------------------------TLDR:In my opinion:Pro's: Awesome developer who will listen to criticism and make the next game much better.Cons: Linear progression. Lack of strategic complexity. Not for me personally because there are better games out there of this ilk i.e Gemcraft and Creeper world."
,Recommended,218410,27920346,"Posted: 27 November, 2016",all,7hm,"Defender's Quest is the best Tower Defense game ever made.  It combines a well-done story with solid RPG mechanics and crisp short tower defense scenarios.  If you are on the fence about TD games this is the best way to ease yourself into the genre.  In fact, this might be the only TD game you'll ever enjoy - and that's totally ok.  It's as good as this genre gets."
,Recommended,218410,17646629,"Posted: 21 August, 2015",all,Aro2220,"I've played a lot of tower defense. I used to play Warcraft III custom maps where the tower defense genre was cut from. Defender's Quest does a nice job of putting a well developed story with well developed characters into tower defense gameplay without it feeling pasted on.It keeps it simple. There are only a few basic towers to choose from, but each tower acts like a character in your party and you can equip most of them with weapons and armor (no weapons or armor for a dragon and no armor for the barbarian/main melee guy). The maps are laid out well enough that consideration to where to place your troops does make a big difference.There is also a nice take on the gameplay by offering 4 difficulty levels. You get rewards for completing the level, but you get bonus rewards for not taking a single point of damage. If you do that, you can get a lot of extra scrap (money) and unique items.What I'm doing on my second playthrough is going as far as I possibly can while only buying recruits and never any items on the easiest mode. When I hit my first failure, I go back to the very start and try to complete each level on the hardest mode possible. After I fail once, I will go down to an easier mode and so on until I am right back at the easiest mode and therefore, the furthest out I've ever been.The main game is not that long and there isn't a ton of replayability to this game once you complete it. That is why it is only worth a few bucks...but it's worth a few bucks. I hear they are making a Defender's Quest II and I hope that is at least as good. Even when it is, this is still a pretty fun tower defense and something that feels more refreshing than you might think when you come back to it after a long time."
