76561198081049785,Recommended,218410,33109626,Posted: 1 July,all,Est,"I've recently purchased this game during steam summer sale, since I've been missing a proper tower defense game for a longer while. And woah, what a surprise it was!Pros:The gameplay for tower defense is extremely hooking! I suffered from ""just one more stage"" syndrome. I thorougly enjoyed it!Game experience is customizable - you can adjust how much experience and gold you earn from battles - whether it's 100%, something less, or something more, up to 300%. I personally recommend something close to 200-300. With 100 the game feels very grindy and you have to repeat older stages over and over and over to get some exp. I think higher exp set up eases the grind while not making the challenge itself much easier. There is also decent option of changing speed of battles which lets you fluently change the speed, from 1/4x to 16x of normal one.Game has some rpg elements - you can choose skill trees for your main units and it tries to have a decent story.For an indie game music is quite decent. Nothing extremely memoriable, but it's fine and doing it's job well.With skipping grind by boosting received exp, the length feels about right - about 20-25 hours to 100% I imagine. Very good value for current discounted price (~5 euro as of time of the review)The game feels like labour of love from developers and not just a venue for making money. From what I see, it received free HD ""deluxe"" update in the past, and there was an update less than 2 weeks ago adding new languages support! Doesn't happen very often for over 4 years old game. I'm impressed by developers' care of it.Cons:This is one of the worst presentation-wise game I've played in a very long time. While tower defense gameplay itself is a cool pixel-art, dialogues presenting story are very bad - just a still arts with static comic bubble speeches. It feels very lackluster and uniteresting. I'm also not a fan of the art - some characters, like an archer heroine just does not look good. It made story hard to follow for me, and ultimately I couldn't engage seriously into adventure of the main group and what was going on in the plot. I really wish there was anything to make presentation more lively. Some animations during dialogues akin to Neptunia? Some noises other than music during dialogue? Simply text appearing in a pace mimicking speech? Different fonts or effects to express emotions such as shaking of dialogue box to express fear? I'm not sure. Quite a decent writing was sunken by this in my opinion.RPG trees are a facade for most of the characters - for example it's quickly quite obvious that any defensive option is a bad choice, since characters are more than enough durable. I don't think there is any meaningful choice or trade-off in build creation.""Experience as intended"" (aka 100% of exp/gold) is extremely grindy and I don't recommend it. It requires heading back to previously completed stages to grind them over and over to get more experience for the characters. It also leads to sudden difficulty spikes where you find out your characters are not good enough and need to grind again. Thankfully, developers added option to customize experience gain up to 300%, so it's not a major con.If I had to give number score to the game, it would be9/10. This game to me is a proof that gameplay is the most important component of the game. Sure, the presentation is abysmal, one of the worst I've ever seen. But it doesn't change the fact, that it was extremely engaging and hooking indie game to me. It's very well done tower defense with decent and funny at times story, albeit terribly presented. It's a steal on a sale for 5 euros! I thorougly recommend it if you like tower defense genre. If you do not, I don't think this game is for you then - this is definitely not a game to buy to simply enjoy the story or miniscule RPG elements."
