,Recommended,218410,8974726,"Posted: 4 February, 2014",all,Lu,"Let me start by saying one thing: I don’t like TDs. Too many of them revolve around mechanics I consider boring, such as interest, and generally, they don’t offer much beyond the core, basic gameplay expected from the genre. With that out of the way, I’ll try to explain how Defender’s Quest won me over.It’s impossible not to mention the fantastic writing present in the game: The story is overall serious, but the script makes no commitment to sounding mature or gritty. To the contrary: while some may argue the cast is composed of very standard archetypes, it’s still highly varied, and the humorous exchanges between the characters are a joy to see. Ironically, it’s their likability that makes the story much easier to care about, not presentation or “visceral” experiences. Take notes, games industry.While I’m at it, the soundtrack is also a very strong point, and is included in the game’s folder for free. Plot and music are hardly all the game has to offer, though. As I said, I don’t like TDs and what impresses me the most about Defender’s Quest is how it carefully avoids annoying mechanics I’ve come to associate with the genre.In this game, you don’t have to worry about insane resource management (interest) or fast finger movement (since you can pause mid-wave). It’s only about character loadout and positioning. That doesn’t mean it’s easy, but that it’s the right kind of hard. That it offers depth.Going through the game should take you about five hours, but that can increase tenfold if you try to finish all level variations and challenges. For me, it clocked at just over sixty hours, and was definitely worth its price. I can recommend it to anyone looking for a twist on the traditional TD formula."
,Recommended,218410,7821990,"Posted: 29 November, 2013",all,Darcrular,"Hands down one of the most fun tower defense games i have played, the rpg element to it isn't too complex but its plenty enough to keep you playing and doing old missions to level up and earn scraps which is the money inside the game, which eventually becomes a non-factor if you play a mission more then once for each one, but if you just blow through the game things will be much more difficult as is any rpg game. The game stays challenging throughout the entire game with choosing 2-3star diffculities for each mission, and boss encounters on higher difficulties can be gruesome, unless of course you out level it.I have no complaints, aside from wishing there was dlc for more content, but i hear they are in the process of making a sequel so i am excited for that."
