76561198183194687,Recommended,218410,19553029,"Posted: 7 December, 2015",all,Weightless,"Many people called this a ""tower defense with RPG elements"" at first I didn't know what that meant but it pretty much describes the game perfectly.Azra is the leader who can cast spells and also boost defenders - there are 6 types of defenders that have their unique abilities and advantages. While you boost the characters in battle, there also is a leveling up system in which you also add points to certain skills which actually adds a lot of depth to the game - it makes you think about what is mostly valuable of each defender and if you boost them enough for a certain skill to be used.Some enemies go straight for Azra, some try to get Azra but attack defenders along the way, some are fast, some are slow, some have armor, some have an insane amount of hit points. The come in waves from different locations in different amounts.It all sounds pretty basic, right?What makes this game so special is that it introduces new variables and level designs at just the right pace; there is never too much of one thing in the game, it's never a grind, it's never repetitious. The levels were never frustrating when they were heard either; it always just made me think hard about a better defense, who should get boosted and where I need to reposition during the battle. The idea of making something challenging without making frustrating is something they absolutely nailed on this game. On the flipside, if you are convinced you have everything figured out for your defense and even need to watch - just fast foward with the 2x or 4x button (this small feature is amazing).If you want to go back and play the battles at a high difficulty, you can do that too, which I also found the be very fun (the higher difficulty didn't just add more enemies - it also changed what types of enemies and even changes the entry points. Once again, they did a great job of preventing this game from feeling like repetitious).The game has an accompanying story which is kind of funny sometimes. I enjoyed the animations mostly and they were well done. A minor complaint of mine would be that the humor bits would take over the unfolding of the story occasionally and got in the way. I don't feel like the story development was conitinuous enough.The music was pretty enjoyable and fitting for the game. I will say some of the songs seemed like they were ripped from Nobuo Uematsu (Final Fantasy I - X, Chrono Trigger) but he is the GOAT.Highly recommended."
76561198097029152,Recommended,218410,19671154,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,surfacepatterns,"When I bought this game, I expected I was getting a mediocre game that would help me pass the time while I looked for other, more interesting games to play.  It turns out that the videos on the store page somehow make the game look a less interesting than it actually is.There's something quite satisfying about surveying each level, and positioning your troops such that different types of troops are in positions that allow them to function as efficiently as possible.  It's fun to get progressively better at optimizing what your (growing) set of troops can do.The second playthrough was a little less interesting.  You're left with either choosing to grind for experience for your troops, or to turn up the experience multiplier (which feels like cheating to me), so I can't say there's much replay value.  However, that shouldn't stop you from buying the game and playing through once, if you're so inclined.7.5/10."
