,Recommended,218410,8892939,"Posted: 28 January, 2014",all,BrightRayKnight,"When I first read reports about Defender's Quest and watched the initial trailer, I was expecting a pretty standard RPG plot and characters. Much to my delight, I was half-wrong. The plot might be your tried and true ""unlikely hero saves the world because, well, destiny"" fare, but the characters and the writing are frequently reminiscent of the humor that characterized the Penny Arcade: OTRSPOD games.One notable feature of the game is that it does engage in some of the good, old-fashioned grinding that some RPGs are famous for, but this game lets you control just how ""grindy"" it is, giving you control of how much XP and scrap (money) that you receive at the end of each battle. This allows players to either keep the default settings and go through the basic plot, or to turn up the rewards to max so that they don't have to spend days grinding the same level over and over for XP so that they can run the special challenges.Each level has four settings ranging from Casual, where enemies have lessened HP and damage potential, to Extreme, where you better be ready because foes will WRECK an underpowered group. Playing extreme challenges unlock rewards for your party, giving you unique equipment and larger XP and scrap rewards, so there is a reason to tackle these challenges.A new game+ feature is a welcome sight, and the fact that this mode allows you to unlock upgrades for your unique gear gives you an incentive to play again.Overall, I found the game to be fun and engaging, well worth the price of admission."
,Recommended,218410,8895318,"Posted: 28 January, 2014",all,blh92385,"Fun game, enjoyable mix of strategy/RPG/Tower defense. It has a bit of a storyline to it although it's not the best writing. Some of the stuff the characters say is kind of funny at times though. The berserker for example, at the start of one battle decided that he wanted to fight with no pants on and said that's how real men fight or something along those lines. I lol'd. It does however get a bit repetetive after a while and beating heroic difficulties requires playing maps over and over to level up your characters which I just didn't have the dedication to do. But overall it was a fun experience. Note - I only paid about $1.75 for the game when it was on sale. I found it to be worth that but it may not be worth the full price. I got 20 hours of gameplay out of it for less than 2 bucks so that was a bargain to me."
